>3. Guild affiliation (if any)<br>4. Raid Zone/Location<br>5. Date of Raid<br><br>When the user hits the submit button, a script could process the form data and figure out the number of raids scheduled by this character and also by this guild, then do a simple check to see if it causes the person/guild to be over the number of allowed raids.  If so, the raid is not posted.  If not, the raid is posted with all the relevant information.<br><br>This kind of a setup would control the number of raids for a given situation for specific characters.  It would also not allow malicious raid scheduling as each scheduler would have to be authenticated via the script (after registering for an account).<br><br>This setup also has the following ramifications: It would be rather difficult for the script to know the difference between a weekday and a weekend therefore a straight 'number of raids per month allowed' figure would have to be decided on.  Also, it doesn't stop people from posting guild raids as individuals IF that individual has registered their own calendar account.<br><br>While the scripts could consider all entities as equal (guilded or open) and still limit the number of raids per month per entity, there still is nothing stopping people from making many accounts and posting raids that way.  That just means there will still be many open raids and a lot fewer guild raids (IF people schedule a bunch of open raids using alts or other such nonsense).<br><br>To combat that, it would be possible to use different limits for open and guild raids.  Guild's could be allowed to have 4 raids per month and individuals might get 5.<br><br>To prevent any guild from scheduling all 4 of their raids at the same time and all for Friday's, a time restraint could be implemented that allows the posting of only so many raids within a certain time period (#weeks/#raids = no_post_period).<br><br>Ok, ok.  It would take a little work but the point is that it can be done for the benefit of all.  I have the authent scripts already for another app I wrote.  The form itself is extremely easy.  All that is really required is the script that performs the logic in scheduling, which I also think would be fairly easy to write.<br><br>What you would end up with is a calendar that is read-only for the masses yet editable by registered guild members who have been given the responsibilty to schedule raids.  It would also be editable by individuals who have declared themselves free agents that run raids, giving them appropriate limitations on the number of raids they run.  And the best part is...it can all be automated and no one has to sort through emails to keep things updated, etc.<br><br>If we want guilds or individuals to police their own scheduling then we should provide tools that allow them to do it.<br><br>I obviously can't see all the benefits/problems with this so I would be interested in hearing of potential issues.  I'm sure there is a way to get them all resolved<br><br> <p><img src="http://www.namembers.net/images/srae-sig.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uveladorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Veladorn</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Drolvarg Gnasher</span><br>  Posts: 748<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/19/01 2:31:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fluclin71335dragonsandtheplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=970.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://yourpage.blazenet.net/anabelle/triad/valas3.jpg width=136 hieght=200></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RAID CALANDAR GUIDELINES -</span><hr size=1> People won't like it because it will be too hard to abuse.  Heh sorry if Im sceptical, just been down this road too many times before. <p><center><img src=http://yourpage.blazene